{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781683053,"nonce":"OInsQNzgo7yQ3vLjgDyN3BInxZY=","title":"DDL model rejects introspectable shapes: index expressions, INCLUDE columns, operator classes, null-ordering","message":"The schema model canonicalization rejects several index/constraint shapes that exist in real Postgres databases, capping round-trip fidelity when introspecting an existing DB. See `crates/squealy-model/src/lib.rs` around lines 543-562:\n\n- index expressions (functional indexes)\n- index INCLUDE columns (covering indexes)\n- index null ordering (NULLS FIRST/LAST)\n- index operator classes\n- plus several unsupported_constraint paths nearby\n\nThese are currently hard errors. For a DACFx-style tool the goal is full round-trip, so each should eventually be modelled in the index/constraint metadata, diffed, and rendered. Until then they are documented limitations. Lower urgency than the query-builder gaps but needed for introspecting non-greenfield databases.\n\nRelates to the broader DDL-management design (the squealy-model crate as source of truth).","files":null}]}